    about: "Small, fox-like, and unmistakably independent — Shiba Inus are one of the six native Japanese breeds (Shiba is the smallest), originally bred for hunting small game and birds in the mountainous Japanese countryside. They retain the ancient breed's primitive temperament: cat-like in their independence, particular about cleanliness, reserved with strangers, and famously stubborn. They produce the 'Shiba scream' — a distinctive vocalization when annoyed or restrained that surprises new owners. They thrive in households with patient owners willing to let them be themselves, secure containment (Shibas are escape-prone like other primitive breeds), and humans who don't expect a Labrador's eager-to-please temperament. They're internet-famous (the doge meme is a Shiba) but the personality is more challenging than the photos suggest. Like all primitive breeds, they're generally healthy but have a few breed-specific patterns worth knowing — Health Considerations covers what to watch for.",
    summary: "Ancient Japanese breed. Cat-like, independent, stubborn, escape-prone. Generally one of the healthier breeds with allergies, glaucoma, and patellar luxation as the main concerns.",
    healthSummary: "Shibas are generally one of the healthier breeds. Atopic dermatitis is the most common day-to-day concern. Primary glaucoma is the breed-specific eye condition (annual ACVO exam recommended). Patellar luxation, hip dysplasia (modest rates), and chylothorax (rare lymphatic disease) round out the patterns.",
