    origin: "China · ancient (Han Dynasty origin; near-extinct mid-20th century)",
    about: "Wrinkled, dignified, and unmistakably distinctive — Shar-Peis are an ancient Chinese breed (Han Dynasty origin documented, ~2,000 years), used historically for guarding, herding, and hunting. They nearly went extinct in the mid-20th century when the Chinese government discouraged pet ownership; the modern breed traces back to a small surviving population rescued by Hong Kong breeder Matgo Law in the 1970s. The signature loose-skin wrinkles and blue-black tongue (shared only with Chow Chows) are breed-distinctive. They're loyal to their family, suspicious of strangers, and require confident handling. They thrive with experienced owners willing to do extensive socialization and patient training. The wrinkled skin is genuinely high-maintenance — daily care of the folds is non-negotiable. Like all heavily-wrinkled breeds, Shar-Peis have a serious cluster of breed-specific health concerns worth knowing — Health Considerations covers what to watch for, including a breed-defining inflammatory condition (Familial Shar-Pei Fever) every Shar-Pei owner should know about.",
