    about: "Small, fearless, and unmistakably driven — Jack Russell Terriers are 19th-century English working terriers developed by Reverend John Russell of Devonshire for fox hunting (specifically: going to ground after foxes during a hunt). They retain the working drive and the famously high prey instinct: small mammals (rabbits, squirrels, smaller pets) trigger a focused chase response that's hardwired, not trainable away. Adults are typically 13-17 lb but possess the energy of a much larger working breed. They thrive in active households with experienced owners willing to provide structured exercise, secure containment (fences must be jump-proof and dig-proof), and patient consistent training. Long-lived (13-16 years often) — the longest small-breed average. Like all working terriers, Jack Russells may be predisposed to a few breed-specific patterns worth knowing — Health Considerations covers what to watch for.",
    summary: "English working terrier. Small, fearless, highly driven, very high prey instinct. Generally healthy with patellar luxation, lens luxation, late-onset ataxia, and deafness as concerns.",
    healthSummary: "Jack Russell Terriers may be predisposed to patellar luxation, primary lens luxation (genetic test available), late-onset ataxia (genetic test available), congenital deafness (BAER test recommended), Legg-Calvé-Perthes disease, and atopic dermatitis. Most concerns are catchable with proactive screening; the breed is otherwise notably healthy.",
