  "american shorthair": {
    species: "cat", lifespan: "15-20 years", energy: "moderate",
    about: "Sturdy, easygoing, and unmistakably American — American Shorthairs trace back to working cats brought to North America by European colonists (some traveled on the Mayflower), refined into a recognized breed in the early 20th century from the existing American working-cat population. They retain that working-cat hardiness: medium-sized, well-muscled, and notably healthy as pure breeds go. Personality is mellow and adaptable: they accept being held, do well with children and other pets, and tolerate a wide range of living situations. They thrive in almost any household and rarely demand special accommodation. Long-lived (15-20 years often) and easy to care for. Like all cats, they benefit from awareness of common feline patterns — Health Considerations covers what to watch for.",
    summary: "Working barn-cat ancestry, sturdy, healthy, easygoing. One of the most low-maintenance pure breeds — long-lived, generally robust, with HCM and obesity as the two main concerns.",
    healthSummary: "ASH are notably healthy as pure breeds go — no widely-documented breed-specific genetic diseases. HCM is present at modest rates (annual echo from age 2 if a murmur appears). The big-ticket concerns are general feline: obesity (food-motivated breed), diabetes, CKD, periodontal disease, hyperthyroidism in seniors.",
    references: [
      { label: "Cornell Feline Health Center", url: "https://www.vet.cornell.edu/departments-centers-and-institutes/cornell-feline-health-center" },
      { label: "Cat Fanciers' Association — American Shorthair", url: "https://cfa.org/american-shorthair/" },
      { label: "VCA Hospitals — American Shorthair health concerns", url: "https://vcahospitals.com/" },
      { label: "Washington State University — feline genetic tests", url: "https://vcgl.wsu.edu/" },
      { label: "ACVIM consensus on feline cardiomyopathy", url: "https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/19391676" },
    ],
    health: [
      "Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) — present in the breed; annual echocardiogram by a board-certified cardiologist from age 2 is reasonable. Saddle thrombus from HCM (sudden hindlimb paralysis with pain) is the emergency presentation.",
      "Obesity — calm temperament + good appetite + indoor lifestyle = the textbook fat-cat trajectory. Drives diabetes, joint disease, hepatic lipidosis. Body-condition scoring weekly + measured portions is the only effective preventive.",
      "Diabetes mellitus — over-represented in middle-aged American Shorthairs, especially if overweight.",
      "Polycystic kidney disease (PKD) — present at low rates in some lines; feline PKD genetic test available.",
      "Periodontal disease + tooth resorption — daily brushing + annual professional cleanings.",
      "Chronic kidney disease (CKD) — the #1 senior cat killer; SDMA + creatinine bloodwork yearly from age 7.",
      "Hyperthyroidism — common in older cats; bloodwork from age 7+.",
      "Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy genetic testing — no breed-specific MYBPC3 mutation identified for American Shorthairs (unlike Maine Coons or Ragdolls), so screening relies on echocardiogram rather than genetic test.",
      "Lower urinary tract disease (FLUTD) — present at general feline rates; multi-cat households with stress are higher risk.",
    ],
    grooming: "Weekly brush",
    exercise: "Daily play",
    checklist: [
      { title: "Body-condition score weekly", why: "American Shorthairs are obesity-prone; obesity drives diabetes and joint problems.", cadence: "weekly", category: "observe" },
      { title: "Echocardiogram by a board-certified cardiologist from age 2 and annually", why: "HCM screening is standard for the breed; no genetic test substitutes for echo.", cadence: "yearly", category: "vet" },
      { title: "SDMA + creatinine + T4 bloodwork yearly from age 7", why: "Catches CKD and hyperthyroidism — the two most common senior-cat diseases — before symptoms.", cadence: "yearly", category: "vet" },
      { title: "Brush teeth daily; annual dental cleaning under anesthesia from age 2", why: "Periodontal disease + tooth resorption are nearly universal without dental care.", cadence: "daily", category: "care" },
    ],
    tips: [
      "American Shorthairs are easygoing but they are NOT immune to obesity. Free-feeding produces fat cats; measured meals + food puzzles produce healthy cats with normal lifespans.",
      "Annual echocardiogram from age 2 is the right cadence even for breeds without HCM-specific genetic tests. The disease is silent until late.",
      "Generally one of the longest-lived pure breeds — 15-20 years is common with good care. Senior bloodwork from age 7 catches the things that creep up.",
      "If your American Shorthair has been 'getting older' over the past few months — sleeping more, eating less, drinking more — that's a vet visit, not aging. Hyperthyroidism and CKD are very common in older cats and very treatable when caught early.",
    ],
  },

