    origin: "France · 1920s (refined; legend traces to ancient Burma temples)",
    about: "Gentle, social, and unmistakably color-pointed — Birmans (also called the Sacred Cat of Burma) have a colorful origin story rooted in legend (a French breeder's account of the breed traveling from Burmese temples in the 1920s) and a more documented French refinement after near-extinction in WWII. They're calm, affectionate, and famously good with children and other pets — Birmans are often the breed picked when a household wants a sociable cat that adapts well. They're often confused with Ragdolls (similar pointed pattern) but Birmans are smaller, have white 'gloves' on all four feet, and are physiologically distinct. They thrive in households with regular interaction, do well with another mellow cat for company, and the silky semi-long coat needs weekly brushing. Like all pointed breeds with a narrow gene pool, Birmans may be predisposed to a few breed-relevant patterns worth knowing — Health Considerations covers what to watch for.",
